title: Web Components
paragraph: Web Components consists of several separate technologies. You can think of Web Components as reusable user interface widgets that are created using open Web technology. They are part of the browser, and so they do not need external libraries like jQuery or Dojo.

title: Custom Elements
paragraph: Custom Elements is a capability for creating your own custom HTML elements. They can have their own scripted behavior and CSS styling. They are a part of web components, but can also be used by themselves.

title: Document.write()
paragraph: Writes a string of text to a document stream opened by document.open().

title: constructor
paragraph: The constructor method is a special method for creating and initializing an object created within a class.

title: Super
paragraph: The super keyword is used to access and call functions on an object's parent.

title: <template>
paragraph: The HTML <template> element is a mechanism for holding client-side content that is not to be rendered when a page is loaded but may subsequently be instantiated during runtime using JavaScript.

title: const
paragraph: Constants are block-scoped, much like variables defined using the let statement. The value of a constant cannot change through re-assignment, and it can't be redeclared.

title: HTML
paragraph: HTML (HyperText Markup Language) is the most basic building block of the Web. It describes and defines the content of a webpage. Other technologies besides HTML are generally used to describe a webpage's appearance/presentation (CSS) or functionality (JavaScript).

title: image()
paragraph: The Image() constructor, taking two optional unsigned long, which are the width and the height of the resource, creates an instance of HTMLImageElement , not inserted in a DOM tree.

title: dragover
paragraph: The dragover event is fired when an element or text selection is being dragged over a valid drop target (every few hundred milliseconds).

title: drop
paragraph: The drop event is fired when an element or text selection is dropped on a valid drop target.
